the recent proliferation of a spiritualist-influenced vocabulary (ghostliness, hauntings, the uncanny) in the works of historians, sociologists, philosophers, and especially literary critics and theorists.Documenting the hitherto unexplored relationship between spiritualism and modern authors (some credulous, some skeptical), Sword offers compelling readings of works by James Joyce, T. S. Eliot, W. B. Yeats, H.D., James Merrill, Sylvia Plath, and Ted Hughes. Even as modernists mock spiritualism's ludicrous lingo and deride its metaphysical excesses, she finds, they are intrigued and attracted by its ontological shiftiness, its blurring of the traditional divide between high culture and low culture, and its self-serving tendency to favor form over content (medium, so to speak, over message). Like modernism itself, Sword asserts, spiritualism embraces rather than eschews paradox, providing an ideological space where conservative beliefs can coexist with radical, even iconoclastic, thought and action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aDeath in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGhosts in literature. 0aModernism (Literature)zEnglish-speaking countries. 0aOccultism in literature. 0aPostmodernism (Literature)zEnglish-speaking countries. 0aSpiritualism in literature. 0aSpiritualismzEnglish-speaking countriesxHistoryy20th century. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 20th Century .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171766640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501717666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501717666/original  a978-